The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Drone offer worries Delhi
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      Drone offer worries Delhi
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	New Delhi, Jan. 22: India is against US military assistance to Pakistan and hopes Washington will ensure that the 12 drone aircraft it has offered Islamabad would not be directed against this country, a government source said today.        
	New Delhi also registered its strong protest with Pakistan for the recent increase in cease-fire violations at the border.        
	We are against any US military assistance to Pakistan as different from civilian assistance. We fear that such military assistance may get directed towards India. The US, however, is sensitive to our concerns, the source said.        
	US defence secretary Robert Gates has announced in Islamabad that his country would supply 12 unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) to Pakistan for intelligence-gathering in its fight against terror.        
	Indian officials also criticised Pakistan Prime Minister Yousaf Raza Gilanis reported remark to Gates that his country was experiencing Mumbai-like attacks almost every other day and could not guarantee that there would not be a repeat of 26/11 in India. Terror attacks killed 3,000 people in Pakistan in 2009.        
	Pakistan cannot absolve itself of its responsibility as a nation-state of not allowing its territory to be used for terrorist activities, a source said.        
	The foreign ministry registered a protest with the Pakistan High Commission against the rise in cease-fire violations.        
	The deputy high commissioner of Pakistan was called to the MEA today and a strong protest was conveyed over incidents of grave and unprovoked firing across the international border by Pakistan, including the firing of rockets in the Amritsar sector of the international border on the night of January 8-9, 2010. The government has asked Pakistan to take all necessary steps to prevent recurrence of such incidents, a foreign ministry spokesperson said.                                                                                                                                                          
